# JavaScript Coding Standards

## Optimal Approach Over Shortcuts

- Prefer the best solution when one exists. When tradeoffs are unavoidable, state them briefly and justify the choice.
- Avoid hacky workarounds. If one is truly unavoidable, add a comment that labels it as a hack and explains why.

```javascript
// ❌ BAD — silent workaround
setTimeout(() => refetch(), 100);

// ✅ GOOD — explicit tradeoff
// Poll until SW activates; no reliable event on iOS Safari.
await waitForServiceWorkerReady({ timeoutMs: 3000 });
```

## DRY & Single Responsibility

Extract shared logic when the same task appears twice or more — utility, hook, or small module — not copy-paste.

Each function, hook, and component should do one thing. Split catch-all modules that mix unrelated concerns.

```javascript
// ❌ BAD — duplicated formatting in two components
// ✅ GOOD — shared helper: formatGameTime(game) in utils/
```

## Composition Over Inheritance

Prefer composing small functions, hooks, and components over class hierarchies or deep `extends` chains.

Skip classes that are data-only (use plain objects), behavior-only (use functions), or do everything (split them).

```javascript
// ✅ GOOD
function GameCard({ game, actions }) {
  return <Card header={<GameHeader game={game} />} footer={actions} />;
}
```

## Variables & Scope

- `const` by default; `let` when reassigned; never `var`.
- Prefer block scope. Avoid globals and mutable module-level state unless truly shared.

## Separation of Concerns

Keep styling out of business logic. Use CSS classes and design tokens (`ui.css.js`, `--*` vars) — not ad-hoc `element.style` changes.

Toggle classes or React state for visual changes. Imperative DOM styling is acceptable only for theme/CSS custom properties (e.g. `--app-height`) or documented one-off hacks.

```javascript
// ❌ BAD
node.style.color = isActive ? "green" : "gray";

// ✅ GOOD
<button className={isActive ? "btn btn--active" : "btn"} />
```

## Iteration

Prefer `for...of`, `map`, `filter`, and `find` over manual index loops. If an index loop is required, cache the length.

```javascript
// ❌ BAD
for (let i = 0; i < items.length; i++) { … }

// ✅ GOOD
for (const item of items) { … }
```

## Shorthands

Use modern syntax (`?.`, `??`, arrow functions) when it stays readable. Avoid clever one-liners that hide behavior — clarity beats brevity.

## Comments

Add brief, scannable comments only where logic is abstract or non-obvious. One line when possible.

For exported functions and shared types in JS files, use concise JSDoc (`@param`, `@returns`, `@typedef`) at module boundaries.

```javascript
// Tie-break: earliest RSVP wins when counts are equal.
const sorted = [...players].sort(byRsvpThenJoinedAt);
```

## File Size

Keep files focused. Split when a file mixes unrelated concerns or grows hard to navigate (~300+ lines is a signal to extract).

## Readability & Naming

- **camelCase** — variables, functions, hooks (`fetchGroupGames`, `useGameClock`).
- **PascalCase** — React components and classes if used (`GameDetailHeader`).
- **Boolean prefixes** — `is`, `has`, `can` (`isGameLive`, `hasRsvp`).
- Prefer early returns over deep nesting.
- Match existing project patterns for imports, hooks, and file layout — consistency over personal preference.

## TypeScript When Possible

Prefer `.ts` / `.tsx` for new modules where types help (shared logic, APIs, complex utils). See the TypeScript standards rule for strict typing requirements.
